author:1617935825=kevinx
diff:1617935825:1617935125:=37,51c37,38%0a%3c Related to the ongoing debate over the Sapir-Whorf hypothesis is the broader debate over linguistic relativity -- the relationship between language and thought. A common argument used to support the relativist side of the debate (arguing that language affects thought) is the phenomenon of color naming across languages and its effect on color cognition.%0a%3c %0a%3c In a Designing Human-Centered Software lecture, we discussed a notable example of this phenomena as presented on BBC Horizons: The Namibian OvaHimba, who have exceptionally sharp vision, but are unable to distinguish between certain hues of blue and green. %0a%3c %0a%3c In English, we are taught from a young age to categorize the different wavelengths of visible light into at least 7 categories: Red, Orange, Yellow, Green, Blue, Indigo, and Violet. In Himba, conversely, there are only five such main categories:%0a%3c %0a%3c *Serandu – reds, browns, oranges and some yellows.%0a%3c *Dambu – a variety of greens, reds, beige and yellows%0a%3c *Zuzu – most dark colours, black, dark red, dark purple, dark blue, etc.%0a%3c *Vapa – some yellows and white.%0a%3c *Buru –a variety of greens and blues.%0a%3c %0a%3c It is believed that this difference in categorization leads to a difference in how the OvaHimba perceive colors. For example, when asked to identify the one different color swatch in the following two tests, the OvaHimba were easily able to identify a minutely different shade of green on the left, but had trouble finding the blue swatch on the right. %0a%3c %0a%3c Attach:http://www.gondwana-collection.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/both-colour-tests-rights-to-media-tumblr.jpg%0a---%0a> incomplete, do not grade%0a> %0a
